post_text:
HCCSC would like to congratulate Ruth Reed on her retirement from Huntington North High School. Mrs. Reed taught for 41 years!

She has taught English 10 11, 11 Honors, and Technical Communication. Also, Shakespeare's Comedies, Theatre Arts (including Advanced, and Dual Credit courses), as well as, Speech, Advanced Speech, and Dual Credit Speech.

She has been involved in many extra-curricular activities as well such as Speech Team, Assistant Tennis Coach, and Masque and Gavel. Mrs. Reed is also involved in Pioneer Festival Melodrama, One-Act Play Festival, Winter Play, Variety Show and the Musical.

"I seriously LOVE what I teach and working with teenagers, but technology is not my friend. I have been referred to as the Technological Dinosaur! My husband insists that I retire and become a craft artist who can make stained glass windows - what fun!!" explained Mrs. Reed.

Congratulations, Mrs. Reed!

post_text:
Today, we honored all of the Teachers of the Year from each school. The nominees for are voted on in each building by their peers. One elementary and one secondary teacher is then chosen, by a committee of their peers, to represent HCCSC as the Teacher of the Year.

Congratulations to the HCCSC Elementary Teacher of the Year, Mrs. Mary Gradeless from Roanoke Elementary School.

We also congratulate the HCCSC Secondary Teacher of the year, Mrs. Angie Grube from Crestview Middle School.

We celebrate and honor ALL of our teachers throughout the corporation. This has been an extraordinary year full of unexpected twists and turns and our teachers have adapted time and again to do what is best for students. We appreciate all of you!

post_text:
HCCSC would like to congratulate Mrs. Sandie Kruse on her retirement. Mrs. Kruse is the School Counselor at Horace Mann Elementary School.

Mrs. Kruse is completing her 32nd year with HCCSC. She has worked at Lancaster, Salamonie, Lincoln, Northwest and most currently at Horace Mann.

“I feel blessed for the many opportunities I’ve experienced over the course of my employment in working with students, parents, families, teachers, staff and administrators in helping students thrive and grow in their potential. I cherish countless moments of sowing seeds, many of which I’ve witnessed the beautiful blooms and those of which I know I may never personally witness. It is truly amazing the resiliency of kids.”

Mrs. Kruse's future plans include enjoying life spending time with family and friends, working on numerous home projects, seeking new adventures traveling with her husband Scott, and helping in the community.

Congratulations, Mrs. Kruse.

HCCSC would like to congratulate Debra Fahl on her retirement. Mrs. Fahl teaches third grade at Horace Mann Elementary School.

In her retirement, Mrs. Fahl plans to travel and spend more time with her grandson, Julian.

Congratulation, Mrs. Fahl!

HCCSC would like to congratulate Mrs. Leslie Nicola on her retirement from Huntington North High School.

Leslie has been with HCCSC for 25 years, most of which served at Huntington North High School, but also spent four years in preschool.

"I have worked with great administrators and department chairs over my time at HNHS and feel proud to be a part of such a dedicated team of educators. I thank all of them!" commented Mrs. Nicola.

In retirement, Leslie plans to do some volunteering in different parts of the United States, keep up with the activities of her 13 grandchildren, and go somewhere warm in the winters!

Congratulations, Mrs. Nicola!

HCCSC would like to congratulate Mrs. Anena Rolofson, Assistant Director of Special Services on her retirement. Anena is finishing her 43rd year in education.

"I have loved my time in the Special Services office, but other special memories include team teaching at Northwest Elementary with Pam Massingill when I was a Resource teacher there, and the fun I had teaching with Lyn Ocken with Jay Peters as our esteemed leader!! We loved figuring it out together and had a great time along the way serving our students" commented Anena. "I've been honored to be among such incredible staff!"

In retirement, Anena plans to volunteer in schools and her community and potentially moving to Lincoln, Nebraska where they have family and friends.

The Salamonie Elementary School Classified Staff Member of the Year is Tanya Lochmaier. Mrs. Lochmaier is the Technology Lab Assistant.

"Tanya has only been with us at Salamonie for a little over a year, but has made it her home. She steps right into any spot that needs filled without prompting and is always looking for ways to increase the knowledge of our staff and students with regard to technology. Tanya runs tech meetings with teachers one time monthly to introduce new technology to teachers.

Even during this time away from the building during the COVID-19 pandemic, Tanya has sought to make herself better at her job with technology by becoming a certified VEX Robotics Coach" commented Principal Dawn Collins.

Congratulations, Mrs. Lochmaier!
Salamonie Elementary School

post_text:
The Salamonie Elementary School Teacher of the Year is Holly Wagner. Miss Wagner teaches 1st grade.

"Holly has stepped up into a new role this year as a literacy coach in our building. It takes a lot of courage to be willing to put your teaching practice to the test in front of your peers in an effort to help them grow. She has done it with grace and has not only helped her peer teachers grow in their literacy practice, but has shown amazing growth herself.

Holly is always one who is willing to take some healthy risks educationally, and takes the lows with the highs. She understands that not all children learn the same way, and was the first one to approach me about implementing flexible seating arrangements in her classroom – an idea that has now caught on throughout the building" commented Prinicpal Dawn Collins.

Congratulations, Miss Wagner!

The Flint Springs Elementary Teacher of the Year is Michele Wilhelm. Ms. Wilhelm is a Resource Teacher.

"We are all better for knowing and getting to do this work with Michele. She works tirelessly for her students every day. That’s not just a kind gesture…she puts in hours upon hours making connections with families, breaking things down for kids and brainstorming outside of the box interventions that will work for students. This is not her job, it is what she feels called to do to make a lasting impact on kids and families that will allow them to succeed and/or break a life cycle that brings barrier to their progress. Michele inspires all of us here at Flint Springs" commented Principal Aimee Lunsford.

Congratulations, Ms. Wilhelm.

post_text:
The Flint Springs Elementary School Classified Staff Member of the Year is Randy Sands. Mr. Sands is the Head Custodian at the school.

"Randy Sands is the perfect combination of work horse and servant leader. He keeps this ship tidy, clean and safe at the same time he serves students and staff. One of my favorite things about Randy is watching him in action with students who he mentors. He will give them a job that he does alongside of them teaching them how to do it with excellence. As he does this he weaves in lessons of character and how to serve well. To finish it off he will give kids behind the scenes tour or have them help with a special custodial task making them feel honored and important. He helps us serve kids as WHOLE children" described Principal Aimee Lunsford.

“Angie is very passionate about making sure every student finds success. She continually goes above and beyond to make sure students feel supported and loved, I have personally seen this during our most current circumstances!”

“Angie goes out of her way to help students and other teachers. She really goes above and beyond to help teachers find EL resources and to help us understand how to best instruct our EL students.”

“Angie juggles multiple hats in her position. She takes on anything she is asked without complaint. Many do not notice how many different tasks Angie is juggling on a daily basis. She handles everything flawlessly. She is very caring and makes connections with every student.”

Congratulations, Mrs. Grube!

Crestview Middle School had a tie for their Classified Staff Member of the Year! Bobbi Ehler and Joni Ehler are both secretaries in the main office and both received the same percentage of votes! So, we celebrate both of them!

Bobbi's collegues described her in the following way: "Bobbi Ehler is definitely deserving of this award. She always goes over and above for parents, students, and all of the staff in our building. She always does so with a smile on her face. No matter what kind of craziness she encountered at the front desk, she always handled it with kindness and grace."

Joni's co-workers described her as follows: "Joni always makes her job seem easier than it really is. She is willing to go above and beyond to help, teach, and clarify any important information. She has a huge load to carry every day and does so with grace and strength that I don’t see often in others."

Congratulations, Bobbi and Joni!
Crestview Middle School

post_text:
We have a tradition at HCCSC in which each building selects a Teacher of the Year. Of those nominees, one elementary and one secondary teacher is selected as the HCCSC Teacher of the Year. These two individuals are then eligible for consideration as the Indiana State Teacher of the Year.

This year, we have added a category for classified staff as well. Previously, we had some buildings that recognized a classified staff member, but we have invited every building to do so this year. We will be highlighting those individuals over the next two weeks.

We are thankful every day for ALL of our teachers and staff members who invest themselves in the lives of those who will outlive us.

ATTENTION CLASS OF 2020:

Seniors:

I am sorry to tell you that we will not be able to hold prom this year. Through continual communication with the local board of health and other state agencies, we determined that a prom that required a limited number of people and maintaining social distancing would make such an event impossible during this time.

You are all finding out first hand that life is not fair; dealing with this situation during spring of your senior year certainly isn't. I apologize for not being able to make your Senior Prom a reality.

Mr. Gilg

post_text:
Did you know that Crestview Middle School has live animals in some of their science classrooms? What happened to them when school closed due to Covid-19? "During this quarantine, many families have stepped up and became foster homes for these animals. Obviously, this has turned into a 5-month stay, but it just shows how much our students love those animals and their teachers," stated CMS Principal, Chuck Werth.

CMS student Nolan and his family are taking care of a leopard gecko named Loki. The family said that Loki is enjoying spending time with their bearded dragon, Diesel, too. This is just one of the animals being fostered by students and their families.

Do you have a child who will be starting Kindergarten in the fall? Here are details on registering your incoming kinder!

Many of you have completed the Kindergarten Survey (Pre-Registration form). You will receive your login information from your child's school to complete the registration process through PowerSchool.

If you have not completed the Kindergarten Survey (Pre-Registration form), please complete it and submit your form. Once your child's information has been entered in PowerSchool, you will receive your login information from your child's school. Click the link to complete the form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSctzFGV--yctYyOyPkLKsCn3Vs5fsH_fmzW4vpZ6BK4JUTWrg/viewform

post_text: HNHS Student Athletic Board members organized a “Cruise” for any Spring Sport athletes!
text: HNHS Student Athletic Board members organized a “Cruise” for any Spring Sport athletes!

post_text: That's AMAZING!! Congrats to our RDM team...all of your hard work paid off!!! So proud of you all!!
shared_text:
Michele Santa
May 1 at 1:55 PM ·

I love living and teaching in a small, supportive community where I am privileged to sponsor the HNHS Riley Dance Marathon team. These kids work year round to raise awareness and money for Riley Children's Hospital. They are creative, kind, talented, and selfless. Although we would have loved to have held our actual dance marathon to celebrate the achievements of these kids and to reveal the money raised for Riley, today we are celebrating 6 ft. apart via social media. The HNHS RDM team far surpassed their goal of $8,000. We could never have accomplished this without the help from the Huntington North High School faculty and staff, the Huntington County Community School Corp. along with the community of Huntington. How much did we raise? Take a look at our Reveal Video!
text:
That's AMAZING!! Congrats to our RDM team...all of your hard work paid off!!! So proud of you all!!

I love living and teaching in a small, supportive community where I am privileged to sponsor the HNHS Riley Dance Marathon team. These kids work year round to raise awareness and money for Riley Children's Hospital. They are creative, kind, talented, and selfless. Although we would have loved to have held our actual dance marathon to celebrate the achievements of these kids and to reveal the money raised for Riley, today we are celebrating 6 ft. apart via social media. The HNHS RDM team far surpassed their goal of $8,000. We could never have accomplished this without the help from the Huntington North High School faculty and staff, the Huntington County Community School Corp. along with the community of Huntington. How much did we raise? Take a look at our Reveal Video!

post_text: The HCCSC Food Service Department has served nearly 45,000 Grab & Go meals since the COVID-19 pandemic caused schools to close. The meals are available to anyone aged 18 and younger and can be picked up on Thursdays at four locations around Huntington County. Each pack contains 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches.

HCCSC will begin distributing Grab & Go Meals again NEXT Thursday (April 23, 2020). Meals are available for anyone 18 and younger - there are no income requirements. Children MUST be present when picking up the meals. This is a USDA requirement.

post_text: If your student is currently having issues with their device that restricts their remote learning process such as a physical break, display issues, or charging issues, please call 260-356-7812 ext. 8200. Please leave your name, your student’s name, a good call back number, and the issue with the device. You will receive a call back from a tech to troubleshoot over the phone. If the device needs repaired, you will receive instructions for a drop off to have the device repaired and a time to pick up the device once the repair is complete. Our goal is to have everyone’s device working properly before remote learning resumes on Monday, April 20.
text: If your student is currently having issues with their device that restricts their remote learning process such as a physical break, display issues, or charging issues, please call 260-356-7812 ext. 8200. Please leave your name, your student’s name, a good call back number, and the issue with the device. You will receive a call back from a tech to troubleshoot over the phone. If the device needs repaired, you will receive instructions for a drop off to have the device repaired and a time to pick up the device once the repair is complete. Our goal is to have everyone’s device working properly before remote learning resumes on Monday, April 20.

Art students in Ms. Taryn Cobbs class have been busy working on projects that will be displayed at the Huntington County Arts & Entrepreneur Center. The center was originally supposed to open on Earth Day, however, that has been postponed due to Coronavirus.

The students were instructed to research environmental issues that threaten our planet or endangered species. After doing their research, they chose a topic that they felt passionate about. They wrote a research paper and began their sketches and paintings. The photos attached are of those works of art in progress.
